Patch Set 5:

> 4. client access this dir by getattr by name, so this request is
 > sent to MDT0, but the connection between MDT0 and MDT1 is not ready
 > yet, then getattr failed in lod_object_init().

Is this in lod_object_init()->lod_fld_lookup():

        server_fld = lu_site2seq(lod2lu_dev(lod)->ld_site)->ss_server_fld;
        if (!server_fld)
                RETURN(-EIO);
        fld_range_set_type(&range, *type);
        rc = fld_server_lookup(env, server_fld, fid_seq(fid), &range);
        if (rc != 0)
                RETURN(rc);

 > It will need a special error code, otherwise simply return -EINPROGRESS
 > will lead to retry infinitely.

Sure, I was thinking -ENODEV or similar (though ENODEV is also returned when an MDT isn't even mounted on the MDS).  Then the client can include in its "limited sleep/retry" for these specific cases where an MDT is newly mounted.  The client will know the MDT is new from the "lmv_setup_time" and "ltd_setup_time" checks in the other patch.

Once the local client knows the new MDT index is valid, then the client could wait longer for the MDS to establish a connection to that new MDT itself, in case it is busy or has some other brief network issue.

That said, this is probably a non-issue in real life with the "ignore new MDT for 30s" patch.  The number of times there is an MDS issue exactly when a new MDT is mounted for the very first time will be vanishingly small, and we definitely have more common recovery bugs to fix first, so I don't think that will be important to fix until it is actually seen in testing.
